         <abstract>
            <p>Quadrature formulas of the form ∫&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;sub&gt;-1&lt;/sub&gt; f(x) dx ≈ 2/n ∑&lt;sub&gt;i=1&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;sup&gt;n&lt;/sup&gt; f(x&lt;sup&gt;(n)&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;sub&gt;i&lt;/sub&gt;) are associated with the name Chebyshev. Various constraints may be posed on the formula to determine the nodes x&lt;sup&gt;(n)&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;sub&gt;i&lt;/sub&gt;. Classically the formula is required to integrate nth degree polynomials exactly. For n = 8 and n ≥ 10 this leads to some complex nodes. In this note we point out a simple way of determining the nodes so that the formula is exact for polynomials of degree less than n. For n = 8, 10 and 11 we compare our results with others obtained by minimizing the l&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;-norm of the deviations of the first n + 1 monomials from their moments and point out an error in one of these latter calculations.</p>
          </abstract>
